te Gmail with Machine Learning and Telegram bots, allowing users to \"delete, archive, snooze, or reply using AI — all from [their] phone\". These systems connect to email servers using IMAP, fetch inbox emails, and save them to CSV for processing.\n\n### Task Queue Implementation\n\nTelegram bots can use the JobQueue feature to periodically check websites and automate periodic tasks, with scheduling of recurring tasks using JobQueue for polling at specific intervals. Popular Python task queue implementations include Celery (which \"allows you to distribute tasks across worker nodes and execute them asynchronously\" and \"supports a variety of brokers such as RabbitMQ, Redis, and Amazon SQS\"), along with APScheduler and Schedule libraries.\n\nThe job_queue.run_repeating() function allows scheduling recurring tasks at specified intervals, taking a callback function and time interval in seconds as main arguments.\n\n### Self-Hosted Email Server Options for 2025\n\nDovecot Pro is designed for large-scale email service providers, offering \"dynamic scalability\" and \"efficient hardware utilization\" to manage millions of users, with a stateless architecture supporting IMAP, POP3, LMTP, and Manage Sieve protocols.\n\nWhile many experts advise against self-hosting email servers for primary communication due to complexity, there's \"growing consensus that self-hosting can be a viable option for sending transactional and other notification emails\" which are \"typically system-generated and don't require the same level of inbox placement and deliverability\".\n\n### Integration Platforms\n\nPlatforms like Latenode can simplify integration by allowing you to create a Telegram bot through BotFather, connect to Gmail using Google API credentials, define triggers that monitor Gmail inbox, and configure actions to send messages to Telegram when trigger conditions are met.\n\n### Telegram Bot API Updates\n\nRecent Telegram Bot API updates include checklist functionality with \"ChecklistTask representing a task in a checklist\" and methods like \"sendChecklist, allowing bots to send a checklist on behalf of a business account\".\n\nTelegram Business users can now \"connect Telegram bots to process and answer messages on their behalf, via their personal account,\" allowing businesses to \"seamlessly integrate any existing tools and workflows, or add new AI assistants\".\n\nThese findings suggest that in 2025, there are robust options for creating self-hosted inbox systems that combine Telegram bots for user interaction, email APIs for message handling, and task queues for automation and scheduling. The integration typically involves using Python libraries for task management, IMAP for email access, and the Telegram Bot API for messaging, with platforms like Latenode providing no-code solutions for easier setup."
